    en: "A valid will in New York must be in writing, signed by the person making it (the testator), and witnessed by two adults who also sign. New York does not recognize handwritten (holographic) wills or oral wills except in very narrow military circumstances. A will that does not meet these requirements may be thrown out by the court — meaning the estate is distributed as if there was no will at all. Many people write wills that turn out to be invalid because they did not follow the rules."
