  whatItMeans: {
    en: "Estates, Powers and Trusts Law (EPTL) 3-2.1 sets the execution requirements for a valid will in New York. A will that does not comply with these rules is void. If the person dies without a valid will, the estate passes under intestate succession (EPTL 4-1.1), which may distribute the property very differently from what the person wanted.\n\nThe four execution requirements.\n\nFirst, the will has to be in writing. Typed or printed is fine. Handwritten is only valid if the handwritten version is also properly witnessed. New York does not recognize purely holographic wills (handwritten and unwitnessed) except in narrow military or mariner situations (EPTL 3-2.2).\n\nSecond, the testator (the person making the will) has to sign at the end of the document. If the testator is physically unable to sign, another person can sign on their behalf, but only in the testator's presence and at the testator's direction. A signature in the middle of the document with text after it can invalidate the parts after the signature.\n\nThird, the testator has to publish the will — meaning declare to the witnesses that the document is their will. The testator does not have to show the witnesses the contents. Only the declaration matters.\n\nFourth, the will has to be witnessed by at least two adult witnesses. Each witness has to sign, and all signatures (testator plus two witnesses) have to occur within 30 days of each other. The witnesses have to watch the testator sign, or the testator has to acknowledge the signature to each witness.\n\nChoosing witnesses. Witnesses must be at least 18. Beneficiaries of the will can serve as witnesses, but doing so can cause them to lose their share under EPTL 3-3.2 (the 'interested witness' statute). The safe rule is to use two witnesses who are not mentioned anywhere in the will.\n\nThe self-proving affidavit. Notarization is not required for a New York will to be valid. But a self-proving affidavit — a separate notarized statement signed by the witnesses confirming the execution requirements were followed — greatly simplifies probate. Without it, the witnesses have to appear in court to testify when the will is offered for probate, which can be a problem if the witnesses have moved or died. The affidavit can be executed at the time of signing or added later.\n\nChanging or revoking. A will can be changed by a codicil — a separate document that amends the will and must be executed with the same formalities (witnesses, 30-day rule, etc.). A will can be revoked in three ways: by executing a new will that expressly revokes the old one, by executing a new will that is inconsistent with the old one, or by physically destroying the original will with intent to revoke (burning, tearing, or obliterating it).\n\nStoring the original. After execution, the original signed will should be stored somewhere accessible. A safe deposit box that only the testator can access can become a problem after death, because the bank may require a court order to open it. A fireproof home safe, an attorney's office, or the Monroe County Surrogate's Court (which accepts wills for safekeeping) are all good options. The person named as executor should know where the original is stored."
  },

